  "text": "Django's middleware system is implemented through a sophisticated stacking mechanism that creates a callable chain resembling an onion. The core implementation is located in django/core/handlers/base.py, specifically in the BaseHandler class which is inherited by both WSGIHandler (django/core/handlers/wsgi.py) and ASGIHandler (django/core/handlers/asgi.py).\n\nMIDDLEWARE STACK CONSTRUCTION:\nThe BaseHandler.load_middleware() method (base.py:27-104) processes the MIDDLEWARE setting by iterating through it in REVERSE order. This reverse iteration is crucial: each middleware is instantiated with the previous handler as its get_response callable, creating a nested chain where the first middleware in settings.MIDDLEWARE ends up as the outermost layer, wrapping all others. The method instantiates middleware classes by calling middleware_class(adapted_handler), where adapted_handler is the previously constructed handler. Each middleware instance is wrapped with convert_exception_to_response() (exception.py:25-61) to ensure exceptions are immediately converted to HTTP responses rather than propagating. The final chain is stored in self._middleware_chain.\n\nREQUEST/RESPONSE FLOW:\nWhen a request arrives, get_response() (base.py:138-152) is called, which delegates to self._middleware_chain(request). This chain execution passes through all middleware in order (outermost first), allowing each to execute process_request logic before calling get_response() to pass control inward. The core view handler, _get_response() (base.py:176-228), handles view middleware, the actual view execution, template response middleware, and exception middleware. As the response travels back outward through the middleware chain, each middleware can execute process_response logic.\n\nKEY DIFFERENCES FROM WSGI MIDDLEWARE STACKING:\nDjango's new MIDDLEWARE behaves like an onion where middleware layers wrap each other through callable nesting, similar to WSGI applications. However, there are critical differences: (1) If a middleware short-circuits by returning a response without calling get_response(), only that middleware and those outside it in the chain see the response—inner middleware and the view are never called. (2) Exception handling is integrated into each layer via convert_exception_to_response() wrappers, so exceptions are immediately converted to responses and passed to the next middleware, rather than potentially skipping middleware. (3) The process_request/process_response execution order follows the onion pattern: request phase goes inward (top to bottom of MIDDLEWARE list), response phase goes outward (bottom to top), with short-circuiting naturally interrupting the onion's interior layers.\n\nASYNC/SYNC ADAPTATION:\nDjango's handlers support both synchronous and asynchronous middleware through the adapt_method_mode() method (base.py:106-136), which wraps sync methods with sync_to_async or async methods with async_to_sync as needed. The MiddlewareMixin class (deprecation.py:276-332) provides a base for middleware supporting both sync and async via __call__ and __acall__ methods.\n\nEXCEPTION HANDLING:\nThe convert_exception_to_response() wrapper in exception.py ensures that no middleware or handler ever leaks an exception—all exceptions are caught and converted to appropriate HTTP responses (4xx for known exceptions, 500 for others) by response_for_exception(). This is wrapped around each middleware and the core handler, creating an exception-safety guarantee.\n\nThe WSGI and ASGI handlers (wsgi.py and asgi.py) both call load_middleware() in their constructors to build this chain at startup, allowing Django to efficiently serve requests by executing a prebuilt middleware chain."
